FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-07-1 — Magna Carta & Medieval Challenges
  {id:"h10fc-07-1-1", islandId:"h10i-07-1", front:"What was Magna Carta and why was it created?",
   back:"Magna Carta ('Great Charter') was a document sealed by King John in 1215 at Runnymede, forced on him by rebellious barons.\n\nCauses:\n• John's heavy taxation to fund wars in France.\n• His abuse of feudal rights.\n• His conflict with the Pope (England was placed under interdict).\n• Military failure — losing territory in France.\n\nKey terms:\n• The king must obey the law.\n• No free man could be imprisoned without lawful judgement.\n• Taxation required the consent of the barons.\n\nMagna Carta established the principle that the monarch is not above the law.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-1-2", islandId:"h10i-07-1", front:"What were the causes of the Peasants' Revolt (1381)?",
   back:"The Peasants' Revolt had several causes:\n\n• The Black Death (1348–49) — killed a third of the population, creating a labour shortage. Surviving peasants demanded higher wages.\n• The Statute of Labourers (1351) — froze wages at pre-plague levels, angering peasants.\n• The Poll Tax (1380–81) — a flat-rate tax of one shilling per person (the third in four years), seen as deeply unfair.\n• Feudal restrictions — peasants were still tied to the land under the villeinage system.\n• The influence of radical preachers like John Ball ('When Adam delved and Eve span, who was then the gentleman?').", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-1-3", islandId:"h10i-07-1", front:"What happened during the Peasants' Revolt?",
   back:"Key events:\n\n• June 1381 — Peasants from Kent and Essex marched on London, led by Wat Tyler (Kent) and Jack Straw (Essex).\n• They burned John of Gaunt's Savoy Palace and broke into the Tower of London.\n• They killed the Archbishop of Canterbury (Simon Sudbury) and the Lord Treasurer (Robert Hales).\n• 14 June — Richard II met the rebels at Mile End and agreed to their demands (end villeinage, free pardons).\n• 15 June — At Smithfield, Wat Tyler was stabbed and killed by the Lord Mayor. Richard II told the rebels, 'I am your captain' and led them away.\n• The promises were revoked and ringleaders were executed.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-1-4", islandId:"h10i-07-1", front:"What was the long-term significance of Magna Carta?",
   back:"In the short term, Magna Carta had limited impact — John ignored it within weeks, and the Pope annulled it. It was reissued in modified form by later kings.\n\nIn the long term, its significance grew:\n• It established the principle that the king is subject to the law.\n• It influenced the development of Parliament and the idea that taxation requires consent.\n• In the 17th century, it was used to justify resistance to the Stuarts.\n• It inspired the US Constitution and the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.\n\nMagna Carta is seen as a foundation of constitutional government.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-1-5", islandId:"h10i-07-1", front:"What was the long-term significance of the Peasants' Revolt?",
   back:"In the short term, the revolt failed:\n• Promises were broken and leaders were executed.\n• The feudal system continued.\n\nIn the long term, the revolt was significant:\n• The Poll Tax was never imposed again.\n• Villeinage gradually died out over the next century as lords found it impossible to enforce.\n• It showed that ordinary people could challenge authority.\n• It demonstrated the danger of unfair taxation — a lesson remembered by later governments.\n\nHistorians debate whether the revolt speeded up changes that were happening anyway.", difficulty:2, category:"application"}
);
