Object.assign(LESSONS, {
  "h10i-07-1": `<h2>Magna Carta &amp; Medieval Challenges</h2>
<p>The medieval period saw two major challenges to royal authority: <strong>Magna Carta (1215)</strong> and the <strong>Peasants' Revolt (1381)</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Magna Carta</strong> was forced on King John by rebellious barons angered by heavy taxation, abuse of feudal rights and military failure in France. Its key principles — that the king is subject to the law and that taxation requires consent — became foundations of English constitutional government, even though John ignored it within weeks.</p>
<p>The <strong>Peasants' Revolt</strong> was triggered by the Poll Tax (1380–81), the Statute of Labourers and the ongoing restrictions of villeinage after the Black Death. Led by Wat Tyler, peasants marched on London, killing officials and demanding an end to serfdom. Richard II met them, made promises, then broke them. Tyler was killed at Smithfield and the revolt collapsed.</p>
<h3>Worked example</h3>
<p><strong>Q: Explain the significance of Magna Carta. (8 marks)</strong></p>
<p>Magna Carta was significant because it established the principle that <strong>the king is subject to the law</strong>. Clause 39 stated that no free man could be imprisoned without lawful judgement. Although John ignored it and the Pope annulled it, the charter was reissued by later kings and became a symbol of limits on royal power.</p>
<p>Its long-term significance was even greater. In the 17th century, Magna Carta was cited by <strong>Parliament</strong> in its struggle against the Stuart kings. It also influenced the <strong>US Constitution</strong> and the <strong>Universal Declaration of Human Rights</strong>, making it one of the most important documents in the history of constitutional government.</p>
<h3>Common mistake</h3>
<p>Do not claim Magna Carta gave rights to ordinary people. In 1215, 'free men' meant barons and landowners. Its significance for wider rights developed much later as the principles were reinterpreted over centuries.</p>`
});

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-07-2 — The English Civil War
  {id:"h10fc-07-2-1", islandId:"h10i-07-2", front:"What were the long-term causes of the English Civil War?",
   back:"Long-term causes of the Civil War (1642–51):\n\n• Divine Right of Kings — the Stuarts believed God had given them absolute authority, clashing with Parliament's view that it should share power.\n• Religious tensions — Charles I's marriage to a Catholic (Henrietta Maria) and Archbishop Laud's reforms angered Puritans.\n• Financial disputes — Charles raised money through ship money and other unpopular taxes without Parliament's consent.\n• Personal Rule (1629–40) — Charles ruled for 11 years without calling Parliament, fuelling resentment.\n• Scottish rebellion (1639–40) — Charles's attempt to impose a new prayer book on Scotland led to war, forcing him to recall Parliament for money.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-2-2", islandId:"h10i-07-2", front:"What were the short-term triggers of the English Civil War?",
   back:"Short-term triggers:\n\n• The Grand Remonstrance (November 1641) — Parliament listed 204 complaints against Charles.\n• The attempted arrest of five MPs (January 1642) — Charles entered Parliament with soldiers to arrest five leading critics, but they had fled. Charles lost London.\n• Militia Ordinance (March 1642) — Parliament tried to take control of the army.\n• Both sides raised armies — Charles raised his standard at Nottingham on 22 August 1642, formally starting the war.\n\nThe attempted arrest was a crucial moment — it destroyed any remaining trust between king and Parliament.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-2-3", islandId:"h10i-07-2", front:"What happened to Charles I?",
   back:"Charles I was tried for treason in January 1649. The court, set up by Parliament (specifically the Rump Parliament), declared him a 'tyrant, traitor, murderer and public enemy'.\n\nCharles refused to recognise the court's authority. He was found guilty and sentenced to death.\n\nOn 30 January 1649, Charles was executed by beheading outside the Banqueting House in Whitehall. It was the first time an English king had been publicly tried and executed.\n\nEngland became a republic (the Commonwealth) under Oliver Cromwell.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-2-4", islandId:"h10i-07-2", front:"What was the Interregnum (1649–60)?",
   back:"The Interregnum was the period between the execution of Charles I (1649) and the restoration of Charles II (1660).\n\nKey features:\n• The Commonwealth (1649–53) — England was a republic, governed by the Rump Parliament.\n• The Protectorate (1653–59) — Oliver Cromwell ruled as Lord Protector, with almost royal powers.\n• Cromwell suppressed opposition ruthlessly (e.g. crushing the Levellers, conquering Ireland).\n• After Cromwell's death (1658), his son Richard was too weak to govern.\n• In 1660, Charles II was invited back — the Restoration.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-2-5", islandId:"h10i-07-2", front:"What was the significance of the English Civil War?",
   back:"The Civil War was significant because:\n\n• It demonstrated that Parliament could challenge and even remove a king.\n• The execution of Charles I showed that no monarch was above the law — echoing Magna Carta.\n• It led to the development of constitutional monarchy — the idea that the king rules with Parliament, not over it.\n• The Glorious Revolution (1688) and the Bill of Rights (1689) further cemented Parliament's power.\n• It influenced political thinkers like John Locke, whose ideas shaped modern democracy.\n\nThe relationship between Crown and Parliament was permanently changed.", difficulty:2, category:"application"}
);
