Object.assign(LESSONS, {
  "h10i-07-2": `<h2>The English Civil War</h2>
<p>The English Civil War (1642–51) was a conflict between <strong>Charles I</strong> (Royalists/Cavaliers) and <strong>Parliament</strong> (Parliamentarians/Roundheads) over power, religion and money.</p>
<p><strong>Long-term causes</strong> included the Stuart belief in Divine Right, religious tensions, financial disputes (ship money) and Charles's Personal Rule (1629–40). <strong>Short-term triggers</strong> included the Grand Remonstrance, Charles's attempted arrest of five MPs and the struggle over control of the militia.</p>
<p>Charles lost the war, was tried for treason and <strong>executed on 30 January 1649</strong> — the first English king to be publicly tried and killed. England became a republic under <strong>Oliver Cromwell</strong> (the Interregnum, 1649–60), before the monarchy was restored in 1660.</p>
<p>The war permanently changed the relationship between Crown and Parliament, establishing the foundations of <strong>constitutional monarchy</strong>.</p>
<h3>Worked example</h3>
<p><strong>Q: Explain the significance of the execution of Charles I. (8 marks)</strong></p>
<p>The execution was significant because it demonstrated that <strong>no monarch was above the law</strong>. For the first time, an English king was publicly tried, found guilty of treason and beheaded. This challenged the idea of Divine Right and showed that Parliament had the power to hold the king to account.</p>
<p>It also had long-term significance for <strong>constitutional development</strong>. The execution proved that monarchy was not untouchable, paving the way for the Glorious Revolution (1688) and the Bill of Rights (1689), which established that the king must rule with Parliament's consent.</p>
<h3>Common mistake</h3>
<p>Do not describe the Civil War as simply a fight between 'good' Parliament and 'bad' king. Both sides had genuine grievances. Many people were reluctant to choose sides, and the decision to execute Charles was deeply controversial even among Parliamentarians.</p>`
});

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-07-3 — Suffragettes & Workers' Rights
  {id:"h10fc-07-3-1", islandId:"h10i-07-3", front:"Who were the Chartists and what did they want?",
   back:"The Chartists were a working-class movement of the 1830s–40s who campaigned for political reform through 'The People's Charter' (1838).\n\nThe six demands:\n1. Universal male suffrage (votes for all men).\n2. Secret ballot.\n3. No property qualification for MPs.\n4. Payment of MPs (so working men could serve).\n5. Equal-sized constituencies.\n6. Annual parliaments.\n\nThey used petitions (millions of signatures), mass meetings and some violence. The movement declined after 1848, but five of the six demands were eventually achieved.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-3-2", islandId:"h10i-07-3", front:"What was the difference between the suffragists and the suffragettes?",
   back:"Suffragists (NUWSS — National Union of Women's Suffrage Societies):\n• Led by Millicent Fawcett.\n• Founded 1897.\n• Used peaceful, legal methods: petitions, marches, lobbying MPs.\n• Believed in gradual change through persuasion.\n\nSuffragettes (WSPU — Women's Social and Political Union):\n• Led by Emmeline Pankhurst.\n• Founded 1903.\n• Used militant tactics: arson, smashing windows, hunger strikes, chaining themselves to railings.\n• Motto: 'Deeds not words'.\n\nBoth groups wanted votes for women but disagreed on methods.", difficulty:1, category:"definition"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-3-3", islandId:"h10i-07-3", front:"How did women gain the vote?",
   back:"Key milestones:\n\n• 1918 — Representation of the People Act gave the vote to women over 30 who met a property qualification (and all men over 21). About 8.4 million women could vote.\n• 1928 — Equal Franchise Act gave women the vote on the same terms as men (over 21).\n\nFactors in winning the vote:\n• Suffragist campaigning raised awareness over decades.\n• Suffragette militancy kept the issue in the headlines (though some argue it was counterproductive).\n• Women's work during WWI proved their capability and patriotism.\n• Changing attitudes — the war challenged traditional gender roles.\n\nHistorians debate which factor was most important.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-3-4", islandId:"h10i-07-3", front:"What was the General Strike of 1926?",
   back:"The General Strike (4–12 May 1926) was a nationwide strike in support of coal miners.\n\nBackground: mine owners wanted to cut wages and increase hours. The miners' slogan was 'Not a penny off the pay, not a minute on the day'.\n\nThe TUC (Trades Union Congress) called out workers in key industries: transport, docks, gas, electricity, printing. Around 1.7 million workers went on strike.\n\nThe government used volunteers, troops and the BBC to maintain services. After nine days, the TUC called off the strike. Miners held out until November but were forced back on worse terms.\n\nThe 1927 Trade Disputes Act restricted future strikes.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-07-3-5", islandId:"h10i-07-3", front:"How did trade unions improve workers' rights?",
   back:"Trade unions campaigned for better conditions over decades:\n\n• Early unions faced repression — the Tolpuddle Martyrs (1834) were transported to Australia for forming a union.\n• 1871 Trade Union Act — legalised trade unions.\n• Unions won shorter hours, better pay and safer conditions through collective bargaining and strikes.\n• The Labour Party (founded 1900) gave workers political representation.\n• The General Strike (1926) showed the power and limits of industrial action.\n• Post-1945 — unions helped shape the welfare state and NHS.\n\nTrade unions transformed the lives of working people by giving them collective bargaining power.", difficulty:2, category:"application"}
);
